WEBVTT

00:06.583 --> 00:07.834
(MONITOR BEEPS)

00:07.917 --> 00:10.000
SISTER: (ON PHONE) Mom fell
and I think she broke her hip.

00:10.083 --> 00:11.166
(SIREN WAILING)

00:11.250 --> 00:13.542
MAN: A hip operation
doesn't take six hours.

00:14.417 --> 00:15.834
STEVE BURROWS:
The neurologist told us...

00:16.291 --> 00:17.583
"Your mom is in a coma."

00:18.375 --> 00:21.583
And now it's brutally clear.
I need a lawyer.

00:22.417 --> 00:24.667
LAWYER: The medical profession
needs to be accountable

00:24.750 --> 00:25.792
for the errors.

00:26.583 --> 00:28.583
We're not learning
from our mistakes.

00:29.166 --> 00:31.125
This has taken over
our lives.

00:31.959 --> 00:33.583
(RAPID BEEPING)

00:33.667 --> 00:35.083
(MONITOR FLATLINES)

00:46.291 --> 00:48.041
♪ ♪

00:48.125 --> 00:49.875
Shane Smith:
This week on  Vice:

00:49.959 --> 00:52.375
we return to North Korea.

00:52.458 --> 00:54.125
(shouting in unison)

00:58.125 --> 01:00.041
(cheering)

01:00.125 --> 01:02.709
Smith:
So the big news here,
today, they did not

01:02.792 --> 01:04.542
trot out the ICBM
technology,

01:04.625 --> 01:07.792
the big missiles
that can reach
the continental US.

01:07.875 --> 01:12.000
Smith: And then,
the grim reality of
climate change in California.

01:12.083 --> 01:15.500
Fifty to 60 mile-per-hour
winds pushing this fire
right off the get-go.

01:15.583 --> 01:19.041
I heard 80 football
fields in a minute.
You can't outrun that.

01:19.125 --> 01:22.709
Robert Foxworthy:
Fires are going later
and are burning more intense.

01:22.792 --> 01:24.417
Something's happening
that's a little different.

01:24.500 --> 01:25.709
Toboni:
Holy shit!

01:25.792 --> 01:28.834
(theme song playing)

01:30.583 --> 01:31.875
(crowd shouting)

01:31.959 --> 01:34.333
They're saying that right now,
it's time for change.

01:36.417 --> 01:38.166
(shouts indistinctly)

01:49.500 --> 01:52.250
(band playing fanfare)

01:52.333 --> 01:54.667
Vice  has been coverig
North Korea for years.

01:54.750 --> 01:56.917
In fact, some of my
first reporting on camera

01:57.000 --> 01:59.792
was from inside
the famously
reclusive country.

01:59.875 --> 02:02.750
I'm gonna lay a wreath
at the statue of Kim Il Sung.

02:02.834 --> 02:05.041
We have to do this
as a token of respect.

02:05.125 --> 02:07.458
We've been on many
government-sanctioned tours,

02:07.542 --> 02:09.583
seen military parades,
mass gymnastics,

02:09.667 --> 02:11.375
assorted government
propaganda,

02:11.458 --> 02:15.000
along with libraries, palaces,
and even their film studios.

02:15.083 --> 02:17.250
We've reported from
both sides of the DMZ,

02:17.333 --> 02:19.542
the southern side of which
I'm standing on right now.

02:19.625 --> 02:22.667
We've covered North Korea's
impact outside its borders.

02:22.750 --> 02:24.375
We've met those who
have left the country

02:24.458 --> 02:27.041
and seen them struggle
to adjust to the world outsid.

02:27.125 --> 02:29.625
We've even visited
North Korean labor camps

02:29.709 --> 02:31.250
in the forests of Siberia.

02:31.333 --> 02:33.709
But, probably,
our most memorable
North Korea story

02:33.792 --> 02:36.250
was our visit inside
with Dennis Rodman

02:36.333 --> 02:37.959
and the Harlem Globetrotters,

02:38.041 --> 02:41.000
which Marshal Kim Jong Un
himself attended.

02:41.083 --> 02:44.458
Now, all of this time,
the one thing that has
remained constant

02:44.542 --> 02:48.083
was the 70-year-long,
fiercely adversarial
relationship

02:48.166 --> 02:51.041
between North Korea
and the United States
and its allies.

02:51.125 --> 02:53.834
George W. Bush:
States like these
and their terrorist allies

02:53.917 --> 02:56.834
constitute an axis of evil.

02:56.917 --> 03:00.458
But now, finally,
and quite frankly,
surprisingly,

03:00.542 --> 03:03.041
that appears to be changing.

03:05.750 --> 03:08.250
♪ ♪

03:24.750 --> 03:27.208
(speaking quietly):
We're here in
Kim Il Sung Square.

03:27.291 --> 03:30.792
You can hear a pin drop.
Everyone's waiting for
the marshal to arrive.

03:30.875 --> 03:34.333
Meanwhile, there's about
200,000 military people here.

03:34.417 --> 03:36.083
The armies are arrayed.

03:36.166 --> 03:38.709
There's a lot of people
watching this globally,

03:38.792 --> 03:43.583
because of tensions
between America and DPRK,

03:43.667 --> 03:46.500
and then the seeming
détente in Singapore.

03:46.583 --> 03:48.583
We're just waiting to see
which missiles

03:48.667 --> 03:50.000
they're actually
going to parade out.

03:50.083 --> 03:51.709
Are they going to go
on a peaceful stance

03:51.792 --> 03:54.417
and not show new missiles,
or are they going to say,

03:54.500 --> 03:59.208
"Hey. We have new ICBM
missile technology
that can reach America,"

03:59.291 --> 04:01.208
which thereby
sends a message.

04:01.291 --> 04:03.917
(trumpet playing fanfare)

04:08.333 --> 04:11.000
(fanfare continuing)

04:14.375 --> 04:17.375
(drum rolling)

04:17.458 --> 04:20.208
(drums beating rhythmically)

04:24.125 --> 04:26.667
♪ ♪

04:33.667 --> 04:37.041
(shouting in unison)

04:47.667 --> 04:50.709
♪ ♪

04:57.208 --> 04:59.333
♪ ♪

05:07.250 --> 05:09.291
(engines roar)

05:09.375 --> 05:10.792
(fireworks popping)

05:10.875 --> 05:14.333
All of the army just came by,
now the people are coming by.

05:14.417 --> 05:16.417
So the big news
here is today,

05:16.500 --> 05:18.959
they did not trot out
the ICBM technology.

05:19.041 --> 05:22.250
They did not trot out
the so-called big boys,
the big missiles

05:22.333 --> 05:24.125
that can reach
the continental US.

05:24.208 --> 05:26.125
So I think it's sending
a message

05:26.208 --> 05:27.667
that they want to negotiate,

05:27.750 --> 05:29.959
to a lot of people watching
in Beijing,

05:30.041 --> 05:32.458
a lot of people watching
in Washington,

05:32.542 --> 05:36.333
that, okay, it seems to be
like we're willing to talk.

05:36.417 --> 05:38.542
♪ ♪

05:38.625 --> 05:42.041
(man speaking Korean
over PA system)

05:44.542 --> 05:46.750
(announcement continuing)

05:46.834 --> 05:49.125
-(band playing)
-(cheering)

05:49.208 --> 05:53.083
Smith:
Now, it wasn't just the absence
of ICBMs that sent a message.

05:53.166 --> 05:56.041
In a sign of improved
relationships with China,

05:56.125 --> 05:58.208
the Chinese Premier
Xi Jinping,

05:58.291 --> 06:02.542
sent his right-hand man,
Li Zhanshu, to attend
the celebration.

06:03.000 --> 06:04.667
Now, when it comes
to North Korea,

06:04.750 --> 06:07.750
these kinds of
political signals
have huge significance.

06:07.834 --> 06:12.333
Why? Well, because the DPRK
has been forced to communicate
in different ways

06:12.417 --> 06:15.000
due to its being considered
a pariah state.

06:15.667 --> 06:18.709
For decades, it's been
almost universally condemned

06:18.792 --> 06:20.709
for its serious
human rights abuses,

06:20.792 --> 06:23.458
but especially for its
consistent, aggressive,

06:23.542 --> 06:25.834
and frequent nuclear
saber rattling.

06:26.208 --> 06:29.208
In the summer of 2017,
relations with the US

06:29.291 --> 06:31.834
seemed to reach a new low,
with President Trump

06:31.917 --> 06:34.375
and Chairman Kim Jong Un
trading insults

06:34.458 --> 06:36.583
that seemingly threatened
all-out war.

06:36.667 --> 06:39.792
Rocket Man is on a suicide
mission for himself.

06:39.875 --> 06:41.834
Newswoman: The North Korean
leader reacted,

06:41.917 --> 06:43.500
calling him a "dotard."

06:43.583 --> 06:46.750
President Trump:
North Korea best not
make any more threats

06:46.834 --> 06:49.000
to the United States.

06:49.083 --> 06:52.750
They will be met
with fire and fury

06:52.834 --> 06:55.500
like the world
has never seen.

06:55.583 --> 06:58.709
♪ ♪

06:58.792 --> 07:02.792
Smith: Then suddenly,
and very surprisingly,
everything changed.

07:02.875 --> 07:05.250
At a hastily organized
summit in Singapore,

07:05.333 --> 07:07.458
President Trump met
with Kim Jong Un,

07:07.542 --> 07:10.750
the first time a sitting
president has ever met
a North Korean leader

07:10.834 --> 07:15.750
and reaffirmed
an agreement to denuclearize
the Korean Peninsula.

07:15.834 --> 07:18.291
I was really being tough,
and so was he.

07:18.375 --> 07:22.125
And we would go back and forth,
and then we fell in love.

07:22.792 --> 07:25.041
Smith:
Now, on top of this
landmark agreement,

07:25.125 --> 07:28.417
North and South Korea
began a series of
bilateral summits,

07:28.500 --> 07:31.917
that have, in a show
of good faith, demined
part of the DMZ,

07:32.000 --> 07:35.000
taken down guard towers,
and even, symbolically,

07:35.083 --> 07:37.291
shaken hands
across the border.

07:37.375 --> 07:40.291
Now, this was
not only unthinkable
a few months earlier,

07:40.375 --> 07:42.333
but is perhaps the most
remarkable moment

07:42.417 --> 07:43.959
in the history
of the two countries

07:44.041 --> 07:47.291
since the cessation
of violence 70 years ago.

07:47.375 --> 07:48.667
(applause)

07:49.417 --> 07:51.917
We wanted to go
to Pyongyang
for ourselves,

07:52.000 --> 07:53.959
to see if North Korea
was really ready

07:54.041 --> 07:56.583
to come in from
the proverbial cold.

07:57.166 --> 07:59.709
There's still only one way
to travel in North Korea,

07:59.792 --> 08:01.500
and that's
on a tightly scheduled,

08:01.583 --> 08:03.250
government-sanctioned tour.

08:03.333 --> 08:08.750
We're here in Pyongyang
to see the 70th anniversary
of statehood,

08:08.834 --> 08:12.250
so we're going to go
through the process
of seeing various things.

08:12.333 --> 08:15.583
This, for example,
is a recreation of the
birthplace of Kim Il Sung,

08:15.667 --> 08:18.834
the eternal president
of the DPRK.

08:21.083 --> 08:22.917
♪ ♪

08:24.125 --> 08:26.250
(tour guide speaking)

08:42.000 --> 08:44.792
Smith:
Now, North Korea may indeed
be looking toward its future,

08:44.875 --> 08:47.000
but remain obsessed
with their past,

08:47.083 --> 08:50.792
as evidenced by this
politically charged,
and, honestly, quite odd

08:50.875 --> 08:53.667
homage to its current
and never-ending president,

08:53.750 --> 08:56.291
the long-deceased
Kim Il Sung.

08:56.375 --> 08:58.417
♪ ♪

08:59.500 --> 09:01.333
So, this is the magical well

09:01.417 --> 09:04.667
that Kim Il Sung,
the eternal president, used.

09:04.750 --> 09:06.959
♪ ♪

09:08.959 --> 09:11.834
If it's magic,
I wish to be happy.

09:13.250 --> 09:15.041
-Mm. It's good.
-(tour guide speaks)

09:15.125 --> 09:17.792
No, you don't put it back.
Oh, sorry. Sorry.

09:18.375 --> 09:20.417
I did a bad thing.

09:21.375 --> 09:25.625
I put my own water
into the magic water.

09:28.166 --> 09:31.542
What started with
the best intentions,
ended poorly.

09:31.625 --> 09:35.750
♪ ♪

09:37.875 --> 09:39.959
More than ever,
the North Koreans
were keen

09:40.041 --> 09:41.709
to put their economy
front and center,

09:41.792 --> 09:45.333
and show us how it's
supposedly thriving
despite sanctions.

09:45.417 --> 09:47.959
The took us for
an inside look
at a silk factory

09:48.041 --> 09:50.333
in downtown Pyongyang.

09:51.000 --> 09:53.041
♪ ♪

09:54.500 --> 09:56.166
(machines whirring)

10:07.667 --> 10:09.709
♪ ♪

10:21.000 --> 10:23.834
Now, while the North Koreans'
intention was to show us

10:23.917 --> 10:26.125
the great working conditions
here at the factory,

10:26.208 --> 10:29.166
we couldn't help but notice
that everything, from
the workers' lifestyles,

10:29.250 --> 10:32.041
to their quarters,
remained heavily controlled.

10:32.125 --> 10:33.792
Smith: Where do
the families live?

10:33.875 --> 10:36.208
(Mun Jin Hyok speaking)

10:42.333 --> 10:44.625
-Smith: Oh, right, right.
They're not married.
-Yeah, yeah.

10:44.709 --> 10:46.125
♪ ♪

10:46.208 --> 10:48.291
But all we had to do
is scratch the surface
a little bit

10:48.375 --> 10:50.792
to see that these ideal
working conditions

10:50.875 --> 10:52.417
for the, quote,
unquote, "virgins"

10:52.500 --> 10:54.875
were actually quite
heavily regulated.

10:55.500 --> 10:58.041
So, beer
and salted meat, bad.

10:58.667 --> 11:00.542
(Mun Jin Hyok speaking)

11:03.709 --> 11:05.375
I don't like that.

11:05.834 --> 11:08.208
Rabbit and orange is bad.

11:08.834 --> 11:10.417
(chuckles): Beer
and hairy crab is bad.

11:10.500 --> 11:12.291
That's a bummer.

11:12.750 --> 11:14.291
Pear and chickens
are not good.

11:14.375 --> 11:17.750
Well, I'm not gonna eat
pear and chickens
anytime soon.

11:17.834 --> 11:22.709
What are all these posters of
military missiles and weapons?

11:29.083 --> 11:30.458
Smith:
Mm-hmm.

11:34.250 --> 11:37.959
Right. And so this is
a silk-weaving dormitory.

11:38.041 --> 11:41.500
So, would posters like this
be at every dormitory?

11:41.583 --> 11:45.583
Most dormitories would have,
like, a military power?

11:54.959 --> 11:57.291
Smith:
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.

11:57.375 --> 12:00.000
Smith:
If you guys unify,
which everybody says

12:00.083 --> 12:02.041
you want to unify
North and South Korea,

12:02.125 --> 12:03.709
then this won't be so important,

12:03.792 --> 12:06.875
because the military's
not so important if you're
not at war.

12:06.959 --> 12:09.000
Mm.

12:13.083 --> 12:14.417
Okay.

12:18.667 --> 12:20.250
Yeah.

12:21.917 --> 12:23.125
Yeah.

12:27.291 --> 12:28.792
Smith:
Yeah.

12:30.417 --> 12:32.500
♪ ♪

12:33.500 --> 12:37.083
Smith: The North Koreans
wanted to dispel any idea
of food shortages,

12:37.166 --> 12:38.875
and to show us their
self-reliance,

12:38.959 --> 12:43.458
so we left Pyongyang
for a collective farm
east of the city.

12:46.000 --> 12:48.041
♪ ♪

12:49.875 --> 12:52.750
Farming, since
the inception of man,

12:52.834 --> 12:56.917
has been important for us
to sustain the fleshy vessel

12:57.000 --> 12:59.625
that we call the body.

12:59.709 --> 13:00.959
♪ ♪

13:01.041 --> 13:02.792
And while the parents
were working in the fields,

13:02.875 --> 13:05.875
their children were trotted out
for songs and calisthenics,

13:05.959 --> 13:08.917
for yet another display
for our benefit.

13:09.000 --> 13:11.625
(simple melody playing over PA)

13:15.792 --> 13:17.667
Children:
Ha!

13:17.750 --> 13:18.875
♪ ♪

13:18.959 --> 13:21.250
However,
after all this
choreography,

13:21.333 --> 13:24.291
we had a few candid moments
with our government minder,

13:24.375 --> 13:27.291
who having gotten to know us
for a few days, opened up

13:27.375 --> 13:30.792
and shared with us more
than we had ever heard
from a North Korean

13:30.875 --> 13:33.792
about the realities
of living under sanctions

13:33.875 --> 13:37.250
that the UN Security Council
first imposed in 2006

13:37.333 --> 13:39.333
after North Korea's
first nuclear test,

13:39.417 --> 13:43.041
isolating its economy
almost totally
from global markets.

13:43.125 --> 13:46.750
Because of sanctions,
if you can't import anything,

13:46.834 --> 13:49.417
then you have to make
everything domestically.

13:49.500 --> 13:51.750
-So you have to do
all your food...
-Mm-hmm.

13:51.834 --> 13:54.125
...energy, clothes,

13:54.208 --> 13:56.667
electronics,
everything...

13:56.750 --> 13:59.083
-Mm-hmm.
-...has to be done
in DPRK.

13:59.166 --> 14:01.583
(Mun Jin Hyok speaking)

14:02.625 --> 14:03.792
Right.

14:05.750 --> 14:06.917
Yeah.

14:09.375 --> 14:12.333
Smith:
What are the hardships
that you have to go through

14:12.417 --> 14:14.208
because of
the sanctions?

14:14.291 --> 14:16.125
(Mun Jin Hyok speaking)

14:18.083 --> 14:22.083
Smith: Have you
noticed a change since
President Trump, or no?

14:28.667 --> 14:31.250
The sanctions
are worse?
Oh, okay.

14:31.333 --> 14:33.417
(Mun Jin Hyok speaking)

14:47.709 --> 14:49.458
Smith:
Right.

14:50.792 --> 14:54.000
Right, so the purpose
of the US sanctions

14:54.083 --> 14:57.208
is to make
DPRK not exist.

14:57.291 --> 14:59.125
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.
-Okay.

15:02.166 --> 15:05.542
And do a lot
of people in DPRK

15:05.625 --> 15:07.041
feel the same way?

15:07.125 --> 15:09.375
That the sanctions
are made

15:09.458 --> 15:13.291
to, to...
to stop the DPRK
from existing?

15:15.125 --> 15:17.083
Smith:
But with so much change
on the horizon,

15:17.166 --> 15:20.417
we wanted to find out how
other people from Pyongyang
really feel

15:20.500 --> 15:23.917
about the North and the South
moving closer together.

15:24.000 --> 15:27.166
♪ ♪

15:32.834 --> 15:35.709
So one of the only ways
that you can actually get
out on the street

15:35.792 --> 15:38.583
and talk to people
in Pyongyang

15:38.667 --> 15:40.125
is to come here,
to the metro.

15:40.208 --> 15:41.458
So we want to talk
to people

15:41.542 --> 15:43.500
about the summit between
North and South,

15:43.583 --> 15:47.417
and does that affect relations
or attitudes here in Pyongyang.

15:48.166 --> 15:51.208
Nice to meet you.
I wanted to ask you
what you thought

15:51.291 --> 15:54.250
about the summit
between North Korea
and South Korea.

15:54.333 --> 15:56.458
(speaking Korean)

16:04.959 --> 16:07.875
Smith:
And what do you think
about the summit that happened

16:07.959 --> 16:11.959
between Marshal Kim Jong Un
and Donald Trump in Singapore?

16:12.041 --> 16:15.500
Do you think that's
a good thing for American,
DPRK relations?

16:15.583 --> 16:17.709
(speaking Korean)

16:24.250 --> 16:25.834
Smith:
And do you think
that's a good thing,

16:25.917 --> 16:28.834
that there's new relations
between the DPRK and the USA?

16:31.333 --> 16:32.709
Smith:
Thank you.

16:33.250 --> 16:34.959
How do you feel
about the summit

16:35.041 --> 16:36.667
between North Korea
and South Korea?

16:36.750 --> 16:39.500
(speaking Korean)

16:47.041 --> 16:49.834
♪ ♪

16:49.917 --> 16:53.625
(patriotic music playing)

16:57.792 --> 16:59.500
(crowd cheering)

16:59.583 --> 17:02.458
Smith:
Now, at the so-called
Glorious Country Mass Games,

17:02.542 --> 17:05.333
or mass gymnastics,
the positive outlook

17:05.417 --> 17:07.667
and diplomatic signals
continued.

17:07.750 --> 17:09.625
♪ ♪

17:14.500 --> 17:16.834
We're here at May Day Stadium
in Pyongyang.

17:16.917 --> 17:19.250
They've just done a big show
of mass gymnastics.

17:19.583 --> 17:20.917
In the past, I've been here,

17:21.000 --> 17:22.458
it's been a lot
more aggressive.

17:22.542 --> 17:25.208
There's a lot of ICBM
technology on display,

17:25.291 --> 17:27.709
but tonight they showed
a lot of footage of the summit

17:27.792 --> 17:30.667
between the DPRK
and Republic of Korea,

17:30.750 --> 17:32.583
which has never
been done before,

17:32.667 --> 17:34.875
and also,
they featured English,

17:34.959 --> 17:37.208
where they were talking
about bilateral relations,

17:37.291 --> 17:40.875
and they featured Chinese,
which is very rare.

17:40.959 --> 17:45.250
It was basically a big message
to China and a big message
to America

17:45.333 --> 17:47.667
that we didn't show
any weapons technology.

17:47.750 --> 17:51.083
We talked about friendship
and bilateral relations.

17:51.166 --> 17:54.041
So it's very, very interesting,
the messaging that was sent

17:54.125 --> 17:55.667
here tonight in Pyongyang.

17:56.542 --> 17:59.208
By the end of our trip,
it seemed to me that
North Korea

17:59.291 --> 18:03.417
had indeed been profoundly
changed by the progress
made in 2018.

18:03.500 --> 18:07.083
But political reality is alwas
much more complicated.

18:07.166 --> 18:09.083
So, we headed to Seoul,
South Korea,

18:09.166 --> 18:11.709
a city which remains
directly threatened
every day,

18:11.792 --> 18:14.834
by Kim Jong Un's
vast military arsenal.

18:15.750 --> 18:18.834
As recently as 2017,
there were high-level
discussions

18:18.917 --> 18:22.542
about whether or not
to do a preemptive strike
against the DPRK.

18:22.625 --> 18:24.542
That's how bad
things had gotten.

18:24.625 --> 18:28.250
Today, we are now
demilitarizing the DMZ,

18:28.333 --> 18:30.208
there are summits between
North and South Korea.

18:30.291 --> 18:33.500
In fact, there are summits
between America and DPRK,

18:33.583 --> 18:35.583
something that would be
unthinkable before.

18:35.667 --> 18:38.458
So we wanted to come to
South Korea, talk to people
on the ground,

18:38.542 --> 18:41.750
and see what the zeitgeist
here in the South is,

18:41.834 --> 18:44.250
and if it matches that
in the North.

18:44.333 --> 18:46.000
♪ ♪

18:54.333 --> 18:56.041
(speaking Korean)

19:20.583 --> 19:22.792
Smith:
Now, while this year
has seen rapid progress,

19:22.875 --> 19:25.625
the work behind the scenes
has been underway for decades.

19:25.709 --> 19:29.291
Moon Chung-In,
who has long advocated for
engagement with the North,

19:29.375 --> 19:32.500
is the architect of the curret
South Korean president's

19:32.583 --> 19:34.875
official policy on the issue.

19:35.208 --> 19:38.542
President Moon and Kim Jong Un
have had three summits.

19:38.625 --> 19:41.250
Is this the biggest year

19:41.333 --> 19:44.625
since hostilities
ceased between
North and South Korea

19:44.709 --> 19:46.291
in the history
of the conflict?

19:46.375 --> 19:48.458
(speaking English)

20:00.792 --> 20:03.250
(Kim Jong Un speaking Korean)

20:11.291 --> 20:13.000
(cheering)

20:13.083 --> 20:15.750
(Moon Chung-In speaking English)

20:22.125 --> 20:24.959
(President Moon Jae-In
speaking Korean)

20:37.500 --> 20:39.875
(cheering)

20:39.959 --> 20:42.917
(Moon Chung-In speaking English)

20:52.458 --> 20:54.208
(cheering)

20:54.291 --> 20:58.333
Do you think
that denuclearization
is actually attainable?

21:04.792 --> 21:06.667
I agree, but there's
also the argument

21:06.750 --> 21:08.208
that you hear
in North Korea of,

21:08.291 --> 21:10.583
look what happened
to Muammar Gaddafi,
he gave up

21:10.667 --> 21:12.875
his weapons of
mass destruction,
he was ousted.

21:12.959 --> 21:14.834
So that there's
a bit of fear.

21:15.333 --> 21:16.500
Smith:
Yeah.

21:19.583 --> 21:23.750
Yeah, there's a lot
in the press anyways,
in America of,

21:23.834 --> 21:25.542
we make
an agreement

21:25.625 --> 21:28.333
to denuclearize,
and then what happens is

21:28.417 --> 21:32.083
new things are being built
or new testing is going on.

21:32.166 --> 21:35.500
And, you know,
we're being duped,
or it's happening in secret.

21:46.834 --> 21:48.041
Right.

21:53.750 --> 21:57.291
Smith:
So, the demilitarization
of the DMZ

21:57.375 --> 22:00.500
is the first step towards
having a de facto unification,

22:00.583 --> 22:04.208
where you have an economic
cooperation or military
cooperation.

22:13.291 --> 22:18.041
What's the worst-case scenario
if things turn around?

22:34.375 --> 22:35.792
Smith:
That are open.

22:53.083 --> 22:55.291
There's gonna be
a high-stakes poker game

22:55.375 --> 22:58.291
played on
the Korean Peninsula in 2019.

22:59.000 --> 23:00.875
Absolutely.

